# Project Agent Instructions — MemPalace Section

Copy this section into a project `AGENTS.md`, `CLAUDE.md`, or equivalent agent
instruction file. Replace the placeholders before use.

## MemPalace — Shared Memory Across Models And Sessions

MemPalace is distributed shared memory used by models and developers on this
project. Treat it as the durable source for architecture decisions, domain
specs, and project state that should survive across sessions.

Load relevant MemPalace context before making assumptions. Write durable
facts, decisions, blockers, and checkpoints back so other models can continue
the work later.

- **Project name:** `<project-name>`
- **Wing:** `<project_wing>` (always scope reads and writes to this wing)

Examples:

```text
Project name: fotodetstvo-voice-bot
Wing: fotodetstvo_voice_bot
```

## Load The Project Guide

Load the project guide through whichever MCP surface your client supports.
Any one is enough; they return the same instructions.

```text
prompts/get name="mempalace-project-guide"
```

```text
resources/read server="mempalace" uri="mempalace://guides/project/<project-name>"
```

```text
tools/call name="mempalace_get_project_guide" project_name="<project-name>"
```

## Read Rules

Use `mempalace_search` first for task context.

Use `mempalace_get_drawer` only when exact full content is needed.

Always scope reads to:

```text
wing="<project_wing>"
```

`hall="code"` is the read-only mined codebase structure. Never write to it
manually.

## Write Rules

Write only durable information to MemPalace:

- architecture and design decisions;
- ADRs;
- domain requirements that are expected to remain true;
- non-code constraints or blockers;
- meaningful project checkpoints worth resuming from.

Use:

```text
wing="<project_wing>"
hall="decision"
room="<concise_lowercase_underscore_room>"
```

Write content in English unless the project explicitly requires otherwise.

Before writing, search/check for duplicates.

## Do Not Store

Do not store:

- transient debugging logs;
- secrets, tokens, API keys, or `.env` values;
- guesses or unsupported assumptions;
- routine code edits that are obvious from git;
- volatile task statuses.

If a stored fact changes, invalidate or replace the old drawer instead of
adding a contradictory one.

## Task Tracker Separation

Keep volatile task tracking separate from MemPalace.

Use your task tracker for live work:

- tasks;
- statuses;
- priorities;
- acceptance criteria;
- comments about what is being done now.

Use MemPalace for durable why:

- project north star;
- domain-model backbone;
- durable workflow decisions;
- provider boundaries;
- non-code constraints.

Never mirror task statuses into MemPalace. They go stale and mislead later
sessions.

